</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="492" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1545,2031]" pageId="3" pageNumber="492">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1828,1853]" pageId="3" pageNumber="492">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[668,806,1829,1853]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Epania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="492" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cobaltina">
<emphasis box="[668,806,1829,1853]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="492">E. cobaltina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in body colour and pronotum covered with dense silver pubescence at each side of anterior and posterior constricted portions, scutellum silver pubescent, and elytra with some distinctly paler hairs along suture behind scutellum. However, it can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[1261,1399,1900,1924]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Epania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="492" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cobaltina">
<emphasis box="[1261,1399,1900,1924]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="492">E. cobaltina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the abdominal segments II and III with a band of silver pubescence at the side, the abdominal segment IV with sparse or without silver pubescence at the side, the antennae reaching abdominal segment I, and the hind femora not reaching the abdominal apex in females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
